 of rigid analytic spaces; in others, one has to use Scholze's perfectoid spaces.The second course, taught by Umberto Zannier, addresses the famous Pell equation—not in the classical setting but rather with the so-called polynomial Pell equation, where the integers are replaced by polynomials in one variable with complex coefficients, which leads to the study of hyperelliptic continued fractions and generalized Jacobians.The third course, taught by Shou-Wu Zhang, originates in the Chowla–Selberg formula, which was taken up by Gross and Zagier to relate values of the L-function for elliptic curves with the height of Heegner points on the curves. Zhang, X. Yuan, and Wei Zhang prove the Gross–Zagier formula on Shimura curves and verify the Colmez conjecture on average.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArithmetical algebraic geometry. 7aMATHEMATICS / Arithmetic.2bisacsh  aAbelian variety.  aAlgebraic geometry.  aAlgebraic independence.  aAlgebraic space.  aAnalytic number theory.  aArbitrarily large.  aAutomorphic form.  aAutomorphism.  aBase change.  aBig O notation.  aClass number formula.  aCohomology.  aComplex multiplication.  aComputation.  aConjecture.  aConjugacy class.  aContinued fraction.  aCusp form.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDimension.  aDiophantine equation.  aDiophantine geometry.  aDiscriminant.  aDivisible group.  aDouble coset.  aEisenstein series.  aEndomorphism.  aEquation.  aExistential quantification.  aExponential map (Riemannian geometry).  aFiber bundle.  aFloor and ceiling functions.  aFormal group.  aFormal power series.  aFormal scheme.  aFundamental group.  aGeometric Langlands correspondence.  aGeometry.  aHeegner point.  aHodge structure.  aHodge theory.  aHomomorphism.  aI0.  aInteger.  aIntersect